This page catalogues releases from desktop engineering teams. Its content automatically generated every 15 minutes by querying the Github API and scraping Launchpad pages. The data is generated using releasegen.

  • For a release to show here, it must be part of one of the specified Github Teams or Launchpad project groups. Github projects must not be Archived, Launchpad projects are scraped for tags. The latest three releases are shown for each repository.

    For GitHub badges to be shown for your repository, add them in the README.

6b9a60a on Oct 9, 2025

desktop-engineering

Release/Commit:6b9a60a
DateOct 9, 2025
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support (#89) Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able to parse any tools to install. Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a `.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed. Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations. Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example `protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go` as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as a tool.

snapd-desktop-integration

b8f4e35 on Sep 30, 2025

snapd-desktop-integration

Release/Commit:b8f4e35
DateSep 30, 2025
Fix test build in 25.10 (#155) Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters, while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with `(void)`. This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these functions.

f11d8eb on Sep 29, 2025

snapd-desktop-integration

Release/Commit:f11d8eb
DateSep 29, 2025
Fix test The test test_refresh_monitor failed to build because NULL was being passed to the constructor, which has no parameters. This happened when building in 25.10, but not in older systems, because in them, GCC presumes that a function declared with () has an indeterminated number of parameters. This has been fixed, and also "void" has been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these functions.

f11e812 on Oct 2, 2025

GoWSL

Release/Commit:f11e812
DateOct 2, 2025
fix(CI): Use tar-based images and no longer rely on empty tarballs (#141) This project used to rely on registering empty tarballs as rootfses to speed up some tests that didn't depend on the final state of a registered distro, a nifty trick because registration was almost instantaneous. But it's been a while since WSL no longer supports that, as it validates the tarball contents. So from now on, unless we're leveraging gowslmock, we use the new tar-based images, sourced from daily builds and cached for fast subsequent accesses (instead of using the appx's sourced form MS Store). There seems to be some pessimisation in the test duration comparing to previous successful runs: https://github.com/ubuntu/GoWSL/actions/workflows/qa.yaml?query=is%3Asuccess I'd say that's acceptable, though subject to further improvements in the test code itself (or perhaps leveraging smaller images - thus quicker registrations).

12ab98c on Sep 9, 2025

wsl-setup

Release/Commit:12ab98c
DateSep 9, 2025
feat: Adds an integration test workflow (#27) Looks like we can go quite far with GitHub hosted runners these days (since they made large runners generally available). I devised an integration test workflow for `wsl-setup` that: - Downloads and caches the daily-live/current image from cdimages.ubuntu.com - In parallel, it builds the wsl-setup debian package from git - When above are done: * sets up a WSL instance, * installs the deb built by CI, * clean up cloud-init state, * writes some cloud-init user data, * does some actions to prevent the test from being stuck in case cloud-init fails, * runs the initial setup via WSL itself (with just `wsl -d DISTRO`) and * runs some assertions based on the results of having wsl-setup installed. To support development time, part of the assertions are placed in a separate shell script that we can run inside a VM, LXD container or WSL instance at development time (though some can only pass on WSL), assertions which are really coupled to the contents of the package, thus we should pay attention to them when changing the package. Unfortunately I'm not bold enough to put those assertions in an override_build step of debian/rules because I that could result in unnecessary breakages. My image caching system saves more bandwidth than time. I was pleased to see that CI was taking less than 30s to download a WSL image (building the deb takes much longer, there's probably some caching opportunity in the callee side?). The cache key is the image checksum read from the SHA256SUMS file hosted aside from the image. I had to learn a few tricks to make the cache working cross OSes. The WSL instance is created from the cached image with `wsl --install --from-file ... --no-launch ...` so we can further customise it with other `wsl -d DISTRO -- ` without those counting as if the OOBE script was run, that is, WSL keeps track of that instance as still non-initialized. This whole scheme allows us to: - claim that the package builds both source and binary outputs - claim that the installed package behaves as expected on a target - smoke test the latest images, preventing late breakages if breaking changes appear in them without us noticing. --- UDENG-7866

6b9a60a on Oct 9, 2025

desktop-engineering

Release/Commit:6b9a60a
DateOct 9, 2025
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support (#89) Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able to parse any tools to install. Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a `.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed. Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations. Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example `protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go` as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as a tool.

snapd-desktop-integration

b8f4e35 on Sep 30, 2025

snapd-desktop-integration

Release/Commit:b8f4e35
DateSep 30, 2025
Fix test build in 25.10 (#155) Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters, while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with `(void)`. This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these functions.

f11d8eb on Sep 29, 2025

snapd-desktop-integration

Release/Commit:f11d8eb
DateSep 29, 2025
Fix test The test test_refresh_monitor failed to build because NULL was being passed to the constructor, which has no parameters. This happened when building in 25.10, but not in older systems, because in them, GCC presumes that a function declared with () has an indeterminated number of parameters. This has been fixed, and also "void" has been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these functions.

12ab98c on Sep 9, 2025

wsl-setup

Release/Commit:12ab98c
DateSep 9, 2025
feat: Adds an integration test workflow (#27) Looks like we can go quite far with GitHub hosted runners these days (since they made large runners generally available). I devised an integration test workflow for `wsl-setup` that: - Downloads and caches the daily-live/current image from cdimages.ubuntu.com - In parallel, it builds the wsl-setup debian package from git - When above are done: * sets up a WSL instance, * installs the deb built by CI, * clean up cloud-init state, * writes some cloud-init user data, * does some actions to prevent the test from being stuck in case cloud-init fails, * runs the initial setup via WSL itself (with just `wsl -d DISTRO`) and * runs some assertions based on the results of having wsl-setup installed. To support development time, part of the assertions are placed in a separate shell script that we can run inside a VM, LXD container or WSL instance at development time (though some can only pass on WSL), assertions which are really coupled to the contents of the package, thus we should pay attention to them when changing the package. Unfortunately I'm not bold enough to put those assertions in an override_build step of debian/rules because I that could result in unnecessary breakages. My image caching system saves more bandwidth than time. I was pleased to see that CI was taking less than 30s to download a WSL image (building the deb takes much longer, there's probably some caching opportunity in the callee side?). The cache key is the image checksum read from the SHA256SUMS file hosted aside from the image. I had to learn a few tricks to make the cache working cross OSes. The WSL instance is created from the cached image with `wsl --install --from-file ... --no-launch ...` so we can further customise it with other `wsl -d DISTRO -- ` without those counting as if the OOBE script was run, that is, WSL keeps track of that instance as still non-initialized. This whole scheme allows us to: - claim that the package builds both source and binary outputs - claim that the installed package behaves as expected on a target - smoke test the latest images, preventing late breakages if breaking changes appear in them without us noticing. --- UDENG-7866

6b9a60a on Oct 9, 2025

desktop-engineering

Release/Commit:6b9a60a
DateOct 9, 2025
feat(go/generate): Incorporate go tool support (#89) Presently, with a basic setup where the user is using go tool management introduced in Go 1.24, the generate action will fail as it won't be able to parse any tools to install. Here, firstly, we now continue as normal if no tools can be found from a `.go` file. This handles the case where there is no `.go` file and the case where there is one, but there are no tools to be installed. Additionally, we also suppress errors from grep when it is trying to look for tools in a `.go` file as otherwise we'd still get false positive GitHub annotations, even if the step now succeeds. Since we ignore errors from grep, we avoid any false positive GitHub annotations. Note, for anything that needs to be in `PATH`, for example `protoc-gen-go`, you should continue to use the old method of `tools.go` as `go tool` management doesn't add the tool to PATH. Combining the two such that some items are represented in `tools.go` and others as a tool should work. Since `protoc` uses `protoc-gen-go` from `PATH`, we don't trigger the installation if a `protoc` dependency is only in `go.mod` as a tool.

b8f4e35 on Sep 30, 2025

snapd-desktop-integration

Release/Commit:b8f4e35
DateSep 30, 2025
Fix test build in 25.10 (#155) Some tests fail to build because some NULL parameters were being passed to functions without parameters. By default, GCC presumes that a function declared with `()` has an indeterminate number of parameters, while to specify that it has no parameters it has to be declared with `(void)`. This has been fixed by removing the unneeded NULLs, and also "void" has been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these functions.

f11d8eb on Sep 29, 2025

snapd-desktop-integration

Release/Commit:f11d8eb
DateSep 29, 2025
Fix test The test test_refresh_monitor failed to build because NULL was being passed to the constructor, which has no parameters. This happened when building in 25.10, but not in older systems, because in them, GCC presumes that a function declared with () has an indeterminated number of parameters. This has been fixed, and also "void" has been added to all the functions without parameters, to ensure that a compile error is always triggered if a parameters is passed to these functions.
